{'edges': [{'node': {'text': 'In 1948, a group of post-war dreamers in Germantown had a vision: a horse show that brought the community together through tradition, talent, and southern hospitality.

Today‚Äînearly 80 years later‚Äîthat dream lives on through the Germantown Charity Horse Show, now a premier event drawing riders and spectators from across the country. But behind the blue ribbons and big wins is a showgrounds in need of updates‚Ä¶ and a plan to ensure its future.

üí° Enter the GCHS Showgrounds Improvement Initiative‚Äîa multi-phase project designed to:
üîß Modernize rings and barns
üöß Improve infrastructure and accessibility
üèá Expand opportunities for future generations

With GCHS 2025 kicking off Tuesday, June 3, there‚Äôs no better time to learn how you can help preserve this iconic event and the economic engine it fuels in the Mid-South.

üëâ Read the full story in bio link

Let‚Äôs honor the past by building for the future‚Äîtogether.

{'edges': [{'node': {'text': 'How to gain your horses trust and strenghten your relationship? 
Definitely not through avoiding situations or things that your horses is sceptical or scared about! 
Its through exposure, that shows horse positive outcome. Like a trusted senior horse in the herd, i offer imput, that slowly teaches horse to self regualte and stay in a much more pleasant state.

Through handling delicate situations with lots of empathy.  Staying under thereshold, but pushing just a little forward when the horse is ready. Helping to co-regualte - inviting to get curious, approach, investigate, release into a rest and digest posture, interrupting flight or freeze responses. 
Reading horses body languge here is the key!

1st phase of introducing scary object - getting curious!
Horse is allowed initially to take distance it wants.
I always move away from horse.Horse approaches first - i never go to the horse and i never pull the horse forward.

{'edges': [{'node': {'text': 'This is the no nonsense method for dealing with large numbers. The fifth stage is they walk up and ask to get caught!

But that takes longer. The first four stages can happen over the course of just a week or two. 

The horse in this video is a good example because he is not an in your pocket type of horse at all. He has a very cold and indifferent to people personality. It is okay! We don‚Äôt have to force him to love us. If he wants to in the future he can warm up to us. Right now he just has to learn to be caught so we can start to interact with him. 

I understand that folks will disagree with this method. But it comes from the same concept as round penning. Just in this case this pen is not round and there are other horses in it. 

Horse is given multiple offers to get caught. If he won‚Äôt, then he exercises and gets caught anyway. 

Eventually they do the caloric calculation and decide to save their energy. 

At first the horse is not required to like to be caught. He just must tolerate it. Down the line he will start to enjoy his work and will want to be caught. 

This is the old way that ranch horses have been caught out of the remuda going back many years. It is safe for the horse and human to deal with large numbers of sometimes untrained and snorty horses like this. It desensitizes them to the rope at the same time. It teaches them to pay attention to humans. And it teaches them that getting caught ain‚Äôt so bad!

I know there are many detractors from this method but this is how you can catch and halter large numbers of untrained horses per day, while training them at the same time, in a way that respects the time of whomever is paying you. 

Cheers

#horseroping #horses #horsetraining #equine #western #cowboy #teamroping #ranching #ranchroping #equinelove'}}]}

{'edges': [{'node': {'text': 'On my journey to better understand and connect with my horses, I found an incredibly powerful tool - soft touch. 

The power of soft touch was introduced to me when I started to study the Masterson Method in 2012. The Masterson Method is a technique of soft touch and gentle movement in a relaxed state to help the horse release physical and mental tension. 

I was amazed by the releases the horses offered after the softest touch, sometimes not even touching the horse (called ‚Äòair-gap‚Äô). When I asked why this was so effective, Jim Masterson, founder of the Masterson Method, answered ‚Äòwe are working on the nervous system‚Äô. That‚Äôs when I became fascinated with the working of the nervous system. 

Soft touch is a powerful co-regulating tool. It‚Äôs as if we‚Äôre speaking directly to their nervous system, creating a language  transcending words. 

The power of soft touch is that you are staying under the brace of the horse so the horse does not feel the need to go into a defense mechanism. This is sending a signal to the brain that it is safe (via the sensory nerves), and the brain sends a signal back to the area where your hand is to relax (via the motor nerves). 

In my book ‚ÄòWired 4 Connection‚Äô I explain 3 powerful co-regulating techniques with soft touch. 

It‚Äôs my passion to help make this a more compassionate world for horses so for a limited time you can download this chapter for FREEüòç

Get 3 techniques to help your horse release tension so that you become the person your horse WANTS to be with.

Comment ‚ÄòSoft‚Äô and I will send you the link!

Follow me for moreüòç

#wired4connection #horseconnection #mastersonmethod'}}]}

{'edges': [{'node': {'text': 'I realized today that I need to apologize to my horse Seni‚Ä¶‚ù§Ô∏è

Last week I was in Germany for a few days of training, and I saw such beautiful work of people with their horses. It was very inspiring to see those high-level exercises from a place of connection and with precision guidance from the teacher to help the horse in posture and healthy movement.

Watching others doing this work, gave me a great visual of what I would love to aim for and it also makes me realize that it takes years and years of training. There are no quick fixes, no pulling on the reins to put the horse in a frame. It is gradual and progressive training on the ground to make the horse stronger, more flexible and better balanced.

I have been doing the Academic Art of Riding with Seni for more than 12 years and seeing other people work on piaffe, canter pirouettes and levades, it felt like we were still trying to get the basics right.

Then these thoughts sometimes creep in that we should be further in our education and doing more advanced work‚Ä¶

But then I look at this short video today and ask myself, how could I even allow the thoughts in my head that we should be doing more advanced work? 

We have been through so much together and he has always been there for me, more times than I can countü•∞.

Besides that, he‚Äôs doing absolutely amazing,  following my suggestions of a fingertip, putting his shoulders back to the track, with just my bellybutton and asking him for more lift through the thoracic sling with just a hand gesture, all at liberty, even with grass within reach. 

I love you more than I can ever say‚ù§Ô∏è‚ù§Ô∏è

Do you ever feel the need to apologize to your horse? Tell me why in the comments‚Ä¶'}}]}

{'edges': [{'node': {'text': 'How to help your horse to become more resilient so that they can confidently live in our human world?

How do you become a safe human that your horse turns to for an answer when he sees a scary object?

Feeling safe is the number 1 priority for a horse and that is what the Polyvagal Theory is all about. I‚Äôm using the polyvagal principles to introduce my horse Jaj√£o to these obstacles.

You will see how he needs some time to decide whether or not something is dangerous or if it‚Äôs ok (the process of neuroception).

Then he becomes curious and starts to play with certain objects. Curiosity and play are great to overcome fear!

Do you see how he uses his mouth and his vibrissae (whiskers) to investigate? They contain sensory nerves and send signals to the brain to help decide if it is safe. NEVER cut these!

Here are some tips:
Be a safe spot for your horse through self-regulation 
Never force your horse 
Entice curiosity 
Give breaks to process 
Give your horse the option to say NO
Reward the curiosity, not just the end result

Get my bestseller book ‚ÄòWired 4 Connection‚Äô and become the person your horse looks to for answersü•∞

Obstacle parcours by @paardenluisteren Nieske Pohlmann

#horsebrainhumanbrain #horselove #horsetraining #polyvagaltheory'}}]}

{'edges': [{'node': {'text': 'Polyvagal in Action‚òÄÔ∏è

Sometimes the deepest connection is felt in stillness.

When we stop doing‚Ä¶ our horses start being with us.

This moment wasn‚Äôt trained ‚Äî it was offered.

Jajao spooked at something.

I was consciously shifting my nervous system into calm, safe, grounded.

He felt it and came closer.

He gets curious.

He connects.

He chooses to touch me.

This is co-regulation in action.

No cues. No agenda. Just presence.

When we understand the nervous system ‚Äî ours and theirs ‚Äî we open the door to a whole new level of connection.

What does your horse do when you just sit and relaxüòä?

#TrueConnection #wired4connection  #PolyvagalPrinciples #NervousSystemRegulation'}}]}

{'edges': [{'node': {'text': 'Morning barn check ‚úÖ First thing we look for? Our FireHorse Rescue Kit right where everyone can see it üî•üêéüõ°Ô∏è

{'edges': [{'node': {'text': 'Did not get video but this horse started off with white-eyed head throws and rearing up with just the slightest suggestion that I might put something in her mouth. Teeth are good. What methods do people use for this type of thing? I just breathe deep and slow and feel no anger or frustration. Then accustom her to polite touching on the muzzle and in the mouth. In extreme cases I will resort to a salted or sugared mouthpiece. Doing these things in a casual and relaxed way don‚Äôt get immediate results but seem to work over the course of several sessions. There are a lot of other things I try sometimes depending on what I believe the root of the horses concern to be, but I‚Äôd like to know what other folks do. #horses #bridlehorse #snafflebit #curbbit #western #ranch #equestrian #horsemanship.'}}]}

{'edges': [{'node': {'text': '1. IS THIS THING ON MY BACK FOREVER NOW?

We might take it for granted that the saddle gets cinched up, and will then be taken off later. This is obvious to us. But a young horse does not necessarily understand this. 

He might be concerned that what you attached to his back is now with him for life! How would he know otherwise? This is why before girthing up we will have put the saddle pad on and off a few times and then put the saddle on and off a few times. To demonstrate that it is not permanent. 

This same concept applies to anything you do for the first time that could be interpreted as permanent. Haltering, getting tied to a fence, hobbling, etc. 

Make the first experience short and sweet so they don‚Äôt have to worry about not being able to return to their old way of being. 

2. IF I HOP AROUND WILL THIS THING COME OFF MY BACK?

Opinions vary on this but it is my belief that the most POLITE thing to do, is allow them to try to throw the saddle off if they feel inclined to.

Otherwise they will always wonder about it their whole life!

This means let go of the lead, let them loose, and give them a chance to see that the saddle will not come off. 

Don‚Äôt overdo it and let jumping around become a habit. In the future you may need to keep a hold of the lead rope and bend them around to show that bucking is not wanted. But it is polite to give them at least one chance to try. And most horses just try once or twice, and then it‚Äôs over for life. 

Do this early on, so they can move past it and not carry the idea with them. 

AFTER, they see that the saddle will not come off (hopefully you put in on right) then YOU take it off for them as soon as they relax. 

This can all happen in 5 minutes and it is an easy way to demonstrate and communicate to the horse the answers to the things it is wondering about the saddle. 

With these concerns alleviated, you can now move on to bigger and better things!

#coltstarting #horsemanship #buckinghorse #westernhorse #westernriding #equinetrainimg #equinelove #ranchliving'}}]}

{'edges': [{'node': {'text': "Here‚Äôs baby Lion out and about for the first time this year! He is such a clever little man and a beautiful example of holding horses back and doing the work to build them up and condition their bodies to a totally different way of life. If you put the fitness work in out hacking and teach your horses a way of going on the flat that will support their bodies, they really do fly when the get going. So proud of this little man!

You might notice that when we are taking the babies out and they are first learning to jump, we always over emphasise the release over fences. This is because when they are learning, they will sometimes jump something bigger than anticipated and you never want to catch them in the mouth or get left behind. Both of these things can freak a baby out, and you want the early experiences of jumping to be as positive as possible.

We are so lucky to work with these horses! Lion was one we were desperate to have, we went around to fuss him everytime we were at the yard. I think we were pestering John and Sarah about him for over a year before we got the call that he was coming up for sale!

We are forever grateful to Sarah and the whole of Team O‚ÄôShea for trusting us with these special horses.

I'm also so proud of my sister. This is the part of their journey that I always do. I absolutely adore teaching babies to jump and making sure it's all positive and that they can get it right first time. Of course, it's no surprise that my sister always does a good job but I'm proud of her for everything she's been doing since my accident. Miss doing this so much."}}]}

{'edges': [{'node': {'text': "BRC winter Championships 2025!

Our 6th British Riding club champs with HDRC and it really didn‚Äôt disappoint! I know the video is over a month late, life has been crazy, but we're still over the moon with our baby pony and our golden oldie for winning the championship out of 126 combinations!

We took our old faithful, Rose, and had a last minute addition because one of the 70 team horses pulled up lame. All of our horses are either over qualified for 70 or not quite ready, aside from a little, unassuming youngster who had only had two outings and never competed before. So Rose and Lion travelled 5 hours up to Grantham and settled beautifully into their stables for the night.

The Lion Strikes came out, dealt with his first warm up like a pro, then went into a full up, championship course with flowers, flags and fillers and didn‚Äôt look at a single thing. Lauren got a little excited and started going for speed towards the end which led to two poles but in his first ever round of jumping, we were over the moon! Then he did an amazing clear in his second, even more challenging round! Beyond proud of our little man, and a little bit proud of the work we put in at home over the winter solidifying his foundations.

Rose was just beyond really. She‚Äôs 17 this year and pulled off her 5th double clear and placing at BRC champs! As always, our little mare pulled out all the stops for us and took every turn to win out of 126 combinations! Still not sure it‚Äôs completely sunk in but just endlessly proud of our little princess. I still remember the day we brought her home 12 years ago. 

We headed home after the first round of the next class because we had a pole and we wanted to get our babies home.

Massive well done to team HDRC, love being out with you all representing the best club!

Very proud of our little ex racehorses showing just how capable they are in all walks of life!

Thank you to Arena UK and Equilibrium for a great weekend of competition!"}}]}

{'edges': [{'node': {'text': '‚ÄúOne day, you will look back and realise how hard it was, and just how well you did.‚Äù

Happy Birthday bestie.

I know I say it all the time and you like to disagree with me, but you carry me. And in the last few months you have done that physically even more than mentally.
I can‚Äôt believe just how long you‚Äôve managed to do both of our jobs and keep us afloat.

I‚Äôve lost track of how many times you have picked me back up and reminded me what I‚Äôm fighting for. And of how many times you‚Äôve said ‚ÄúI can‚Äôt carry it for you but I can carry you.‚Äù You have. In every way.

I am so proud of you for how much you have had to overcome and navigate. For starters, you get a different me every day and somehow you always manage to just be there and tell me the things I need to hear.

You managed to sell horses and do some absolutely incredible work with client horses, and kept our clients informed of what their babies are up to.

Somehow, you managed to win at areas, the day I went back into hospital with the infection despite being pretty beside yourself.

If that wasn‚Äôt enough, you won nationals with our princess! Like how?! I mean, I have the proof of how because those turns! But still, it was enough to get there with everything we‚Äôve had going on this year!

You lifted me back onto my horses and helped me jump for the first time and cheered me on through every little baby step.

And then just when I think you can‚Äôt do any more, you go and do a double clear at your first event of the season on a horse you have never even show jumped.

I‚Äôm so grateful to the way you have kept the place not just running but thriving. Thank you for encouraging me and also shielding me from myself as always. Thank you for never letting me fall. Thank you for never giving up on me or a single one of our horses. Thank you for holding my leg still on the journey to hospital. Thank you for being my best friend.

‚ÄúI can do all things.‚Äù'}}]}

{'edges': [{'node': {'text': 'Soll das so? Ruby ist ein Kracher! Sie ist ein Traum, so viel Charakter, ein ganz tolles Pferd! 
Ich arbeite weiterhin frei mit Ruby, wir sind da einer Sache auf der Spur. Ruby entdeckt gerade die Freude an der Zusammenarbeit. Vor einigen Einheiten ist Ruby nur gerannt, sie hat f√∂rmlich die Mittelfinder erhoben und gesagt "mit dir fange ich gar nicht an, ich lasse mich nicht ein!" √úber Druck und Aushalten h√§tte ich sie niemals erreicht. Sie h√§tte den l√§ngeren Atem gehabt, da bin ich sicher. 
Nach und nach hat sie aber verstanden, dass es da eine Art des Austausches gibt, der sie interessiert - immerhin ist sie sehr intelligent und neugierig! Jetzt sind wir an dem Punkt, an dem sie es genie√üt, diesen Austausch zu pflegen. Gleichzeitig steht da aber noch ihre alte Emp√∂rung angesichts gestellter Anspr√ºche im Raum. Sie will sich einlassen, sie wei√ü, dass es nur auf Augenh√∂he funktioniert, sie kann es aber noch nicht ganz lassen - die alten Muster greifen noch ein wenig. Das Spiel mit der Energie reizt sie noch sehr. "Hochfahren? Ich zeige dir gleich wie ich hochfahren! Runterfahren? Hahaha!" Dann setzt aber doch wieder die neu gewonnene Liebe zur Harmonie und Kommunikation ein und alles ringt in ihr auf einmal. 

Ich bin mir sehr sicher, dass wir in den n√§chsten Einheiten diesen inneren Kampf immer weniger n√∂tig haben werden - ich f√ºhle es bereits knistern!'}}]}

{'edges': [{'node': {'text': 'Bist du verr√ºckt, anreiten im Gel√§nde?!

Verr√ºckt bin ich vielleicht, aber ich denke mir etwas dabei und Esmeralda zeigt mir, dass ihr meine Idee gef√§llt.

Esmeralda wurde zwar als Reitpferd verkauft, demnach sa√üen auch schon Menschen auf ihr. Allerdings kann man das nicht als Reiten bezeichnen, Pferd und Mensch mussten bei diesem Erlebnis Angst gehabt haben. Als einen verkrampften Feuerstuhl h√§tte ich sie bezeichnet. Deshalb haben wir den Prozess des Anreitens noch einmal komplett neu gestartet, haben sie mental, emotional und k√∂rperlich fitter gemacht, bevor wir wieder ans Reiten dachten. Ich denke, sie ist jetzt soweit, dass man sich langsam wieder ans Reiten tasten kann. Sie beginnt jetzt also einen langen Prozess, an dessen Ende sie sich nach Monaten, oder vielleicht Jahren, als echtes Reitpferd bezeichnen kann, das auf allen Ebenen zu 100 Prozent dazu in der Lage ist, seinen Menschen in jeder Situation sicher zu tragen. Wobei nat√ºrlich nicht allein die Dauer dieses Prozesses entscheidend ist, sondern die Gestaltung dieses Prozesses (sonst m√ºsste man nur lange genug immer weiter machen - mit egal was).

Auf dem Reitplatz habe ich mich vor diesem Gel√§nderitt 4 Mal auf Esmeralda geschwungen, die L√§ngen dieser Einheiten waren so verteilt: 10 Sekunden; 2 Minuten; 3 Minuten; 5 Minuten.

Und danach ging es direkt ins Gel√§nde. Das Gel√§nde muss keine zus√§tzliche Belastung sein, wenn man zuvor das Drau√üensein als eine positive gemeinsame Erfahrung gefestigt hat und nicht unbedingt an der neuen Gro√übaustelle neben der vielbefahrenen Stra√üe vorbeirten m√∂chte. Viel mehr ist mir das Gel√§nde eine Hilfe beim Anreiten. Wir k√∂nnen ganz einfach geradeaus reiten und m√ºssen nicht, wie auf dem Reitplatz, st√§ndig eine schwierige Kurve reiten. Es gibt einen Weg, ein Ziel, einen Sinn der gemeinsamen Fortbewegung. Noch dazu merkt man bei Esmeralda, dass sie Angst hat, wenn man auf dem Platz alte Erfahrungen triggert, man kann sich denken, dass sie auf dem Platz nicht die besten Erlebnisse hatte. {'edges': [{'node': {'text': 'Love when the 25 year old acts 20 years younger. However, her relaxation and confidence is still our number one priority, even undersaddle. 
I should have added that whenever we did downward transitions, our goal was to ensure Beauty was soft and relaxed before asking for an upward transition, but Abby knows this. Usually this meant waiting for a lick and chew softening of the eye, and lowering of the head(although there are more signs.) This final canter is progress for this little mare who is not only long and built downhill, but had quite a bit (alot) of "go"  in her tonight.  Although it is great to see a horse her age with so much "go" we still want to ensure it is excitement and not anxiousness  fueling that fire. Sometimes anticipation is not always your friend, sometimes it is. 

I think I can speak for both Abby and myself when I say we LOVE this mare. 

love this team ü•∞ü§©'}}]}

{'edges': [{'node': {'text': 'When they are curious‚Ä¶

This lone young bull elephant was very curious of the horses and riders.

On our horseback safari in Botswana on Mashatu Game Reserve.

All our safaris have two professional guides on the rides. Our guides and our horses have been riding with and alongside elephants for many years. Young bulls, in particular, can sometimes be curious and boisterous. In such circumstances, it is the lead guide and lead horse‚Äôs job to stand their ground, to give the back up guide a chance to lead the other riders away from the elephant and take the pressure off.

Sometimes the lead guide will just use his voice, and other times he may crack his bull whip. The elephants do respond, and will move on. Once the guests are away from the animal, the lead guide will also move away, leaving the elephant to carry on his way in the bush.

Max and his faithful and very brave stead, Mpherembi, did a good job here and the elephant and riders moved on.

This can be quite and exhilarating experience if it happens. Obviously, these type of situations generally will only happen if an animal is startled, or appears from a thick bushy area unexpectedly.

The most important thing in the bush, is to respect the animal‚Äôs space and not to cause it any distress.

For more details, please send us a message with your email address or contact laura@ridinginafrica.com.

Film credit @beadlesa Dr Tanya Baber

{'edges': [{'node': {'text': 'An African safari on horseback

Horse riding alongside the wildlife, is a completely unique way to experience Africa.
Being in the bush on a horse is an immersive experience like no other. By the end of a week, you will hear and see every detail, have watched countless wildlife stories unfold in front of you and have spent a week riding a well trained and adapted safari horse. Within our herd of over 170 horses, we have many boerperd and boerperd crosses, a breed which originates from South Africa. A mixture of Andalusian, Arab, and Hackney, these horses have incredible stamina and are well adapted to the conditions.

Join us on a horseback adventure of a lifetime on our African Explorer Safari - spend 4 nights in South Africa followed by 3 nights in Botswana; stay in 4 different camps; ride 2 different horses; and ride alongside elephant, giraffe, zebra, buffalo, leopard, lions, hyenas, cheetahs and all the antelope on the plains.

If you are looking for a riding holiday safari with a difference, join us on an 8 day safari in South Africa and Botswana:

6-13 June (1 saddles)

Message us for details or if you prefer, email susie@ridinginafrica.com or What‚Äôs App Laura: +27-83-419-1929.

{'edges': [{'node': {'text': 'Meet Lambada - new Boerperd stallion joining our herd. 

He is from the Losberg stud in Namibia. Thanks to Loise and Callie for their hospitality this week and congratulations to them both on a successful first auction. Lovely horses and just perfect for our safaris.

Lambada will arrive in a couple of weeks after the vet checks and export clearance is done. Although he is already under saddle, he is still a young boy and will be introduced to safari life slowly to make sure he is ready for guests.

Let us know what you think of him in the comments and do send us a direct message if you‚Äôd like details about any of our safaris in South Africa or Botswana. Spaces are almost full for 2025 and we are booking well into 2026 already.

{'edges': [{'node': {'text': 'Free Movement.  Bonafide Connections. Mixed Forage. 

This is quality of life for a Horse. 

When she can no longer enjoy these things- she has asked us to set her free.  No hoof boots, grazing muzzles, stall confinement or isolation from the Herd she loves. We have tried some of those things only to hear her ask us to just let her be a Horse and live out her life in her True Nature. 

We love you Penny and we are listening. 

We will be here for you and keep you as comfortable as we can until you are ready for the sacred journey Home. 

And even then, we know in our hearts we will never be apart. ü§ç'}}]}

{'edges': [{'node': {'text': 'Help your horse use BOTH sides of its brain.

When your horse responds to pressure rather than reacting, you‚Äôll have a much safer and more productive experience.

You want to create feel around various areas of the horse‚Äôs body to help them use the responsive side of their brain over the reactive side of their brain when things change and become scary.

This responsive responsibility in change is developed through feel, timing, and understanding.

Jordan

#jbh #jordanbrasserhorsemanship #naturalhorsemanship #horsebehaviour #horsepsychology #equineeducation #equinecare #horsecare #horsesafety #onlinehorsetraining #trainhorses #understandinghorses #michiganhorses'}}]}

{'edges': [{'node': {'text': "Let‚Äôs dive into forming new habits this year! üôåüèº

üî∏Ô∏èEstablish Trust:

A horse doesn‚Äôt care how much you know, until you show how much you care.

üî∏Ô∏èClear Communication:

Horses have long bodies, we have tall bodies. So we need to use long body logic in order to clearly communicate with them.

üî∏Ô∏èPattern Reinforcement:

Horses thrive on routine, and consistent training will help establish new habits.

üî∏Ô∏èPositive Reinforcement:

A rub on the neck and a moment of relaxation can be a powerful motivator for your horse.

üî∏Ô∏èProgressive Challenges:

Gradually increase the difficulty of tasks. This not only keeps your horse mentally stimulated but also builds their confidence as they successfully tackle new challenges and form new habits. FOR YOU TOO!

üí™üèºIf you are encouraged to start your horse journey and form new habits together in 2024, comment ‚ÄúInfo‚Äù and we‚Äôll send you the steps you need to get started!

Look for the FULL video of Trigger's training session on ‚úÖÔ∏è YOUTUBE ‚úÖÔ∏è, where Jordan explains step-by-step each training technique to form new habits from the ground up.

üîó LINK in Bio! ‚¨ÜÔ∏è

#EquineConnection #MindfulTraining #EquestrianJourney #JBH #jordanbrasserhorsemanship #horsebehavior #onlinetraining #onlinehorsetraining #horsetrainer #horseclinics #horsecare #horseachievements #theyearofthehorse"}}]}

{'edges': [{'node': {'text': "A massive ‚ÄòDanke‚Äô and 'Merci' to our incredible instructors and everyone who made this adventure possible. üôè We couldn't have done it without your hard work and dedication! Thank you for your generous hospitality!

This was the 7th time visiting Europe teaching natural horsemanship and it was an incredible experience that we'll always cherish. üåü

The clinic tour in Germany and France was nothing short of incredible!

In Germany and France, we had the privilege of working with dedicated individuals who share our passion for horses. It was an absolute honor to witness their commitment to growth and learning.

The clinics were a hit, with each day bringing more eager and enthusiastic horse lovers into the community of natural horsemanship.

The joy and success we experienced are beyond words, and we're thrilled to announce that we'll be back next year! üóìÔ∏è

Stay tuned and comment EUROPE if you want to be first in line for next year's European clinic tour. üì£

Let's keep the spirit of horsemanship alive! üêéüí´

If you're interested in hosting a clinic in your area, comment NATURAL, and we'll reach out to you!

More photos and videos to come from the Europe tour! We have a ton to get through! 

Naturally,
Kristen and Jordan
JBH

P.s. Don't forget to mark your calendars for the Michigan Horse Expo March 8-10! We'll be there again if you missed us last year!

{'edges': [{'node': {'text': "So today was our final day at our little storefront in downtown Peterborough. We had a lot of fun there over the last year but we're ready for a new adventure. Thank you all that came out and supported the store. It meant a lot! We'll be shifting to the Peterborough Farmers' Market on Wednesday afternoons so please stop by and say hi. {'edges': [{'node': {'text': 'Horses go to the dentist as wellü¶∑

Horses have continuously erupting teeth, which means they wear down as they chew, potentially creating sharp edges and points. The way a horse‚Äôs upper and lower jaws are structured lead to uneven grinding.

These sharp edges can cause potential problems, pain and discomfort, leading to difficulty chewing, head-tossing, and even ulcers on the cheek and tongue. 

#horses #equine #horses #horsesontiktok #horsedentist #veterinarian #equinelife #quaterhorse #fyp'}}]}

{'edges': [{'node': {'text': "Hi! It's me after a two month hiatus due to being full force into my summer program schedule at the farm, I thought it would be a great time to reintroduce myself since I had some issues with my last reintro post and to archive it!

{'edges': [{'node': {'text': 'Canter GOALS üí´ 

A quality canter is one where your horse has learned to move his balance back more onto his hind legs. In other words, your horse‚Äôs hind legs step further underneath his body, towards his center of gravity, to provide support and to store energy and power.

Want to know how to encourage your horse to shift his balance and become more uphill? 

Comment below if you‚Äôd like to see my top tips and I‚Äôll share my top 3 exercises with you guys üíúüíúüíú

{'edges': [{'node': {'text': 'ü§î Reflections on Badminton Horse Trials ü§î
I had another extraordinary time at @bhorsetrials with @lauren_innes_eventing, Flipper and their team. I am so gutted for them that after making the XC course look like a Pony Club track, one mistake led to the end of their competition. But, they are unscathed and should look back on a week of positives ahead of their Burghley preparations.

Our aim over the past 18 months has been to undo the ‚Äútrauma‚Äù (for want of a better word!) that Flipper had in the dressage phase of his first 5* event a few years ago. Flipper lives for jumping big fences, but the effect of the electric atmosphere and crowds during that first 5* has not only blighted his dressage performances at this level since, but has made him difficult to handle around the venue and tricky in the trot-ups, when in ‚Äúnormal life‚Äù he is such an easy horse to handle.

With Lauren‚Äôs hard work and willingness to try out my ideas, super groom @derbilldc dedication in learning new handling techniques, and Lauren‚Äôs coaches, Lizzie and Mark putting up with me (!), there has been so much improvement behind the scenes. And, most importantly, it has enhanced Flipper‚Äôs wellbeing at these events leading to a far less stressed and happier horse... the last piece of the puzzle is being able to get the scores that their partnership deserves!

As horse sports come under increasing scrutiny, I came away from Badminton with the thought that the bond between the horses and riders was nothing short of extraordinary. At every stage the welfare of the horse was clearly at the heart of everything.

It is a privilege to ride horses, and even more so to earn the kind of trust and partnership that allows them to perform at the highest level. These athletes ‚Äî both human and equine ‚Äî are a testament to what‚Äôs possible when training is rooted in empathy, respect, and understanding.

#partners #progress #playthelonggame #eventing #badmintonhorsetrials'}}]}

{'edges': [{'node': {'text': '‚ÄºÔ∏èHelp us bring Bugs home ‚ÄºÔ∏è
üö®Latest update: 
He went through the Boone County Draft Horse and Mule Sale in Missouri in March 2024 as Lot 95. He was presented at auction in a driving pair together with a 5yo Percheron. They were sold separately. 

üê¥ Horse Info :
10 yo 18.2h black Percheron gelding, went by the Barn name Bugs, small white star, right hind leg white coronet with a black dot on the inside of the coronet

üìñ The Story behind it :
This is a long shot but back in 2022 my life had crashed again and I was left without income for some time. I lost basically everything. The last of what I owned that could keep me going was my big Percheron Bugs who meant the world to us. I was forced to sell him and it broke me and it is something I deeply hate about myself and life and eats at my soul every day.

The lady who bought him is in Missouri named Jody. In the papers she agreed to notify me if she ever would sell him. He was supposed to be a saddle horse for her daughter. For that reason I did not feel it right to ask to buy a horse back who was for a young girl. So I checked on him regularly and was told her daughter was riding him and he was good.

We have recently found out that he was sold and I was never informed about it and am not being told where he went to. (I have come to find out she lied and put him in the Boone County Auction without disclosing his medical information about tie back surgeries, and listed him as grade)

{'edges': [{'node': {'text': 'FQHR Dancin Lil Mamma aka‚Ä¶ ‚ú® Kimber ‚ú® was just 8 months old when she became a part of Ellie Almond‚Äôs life. At age three, she came to me for six months of training to get her started under gunfire, and even then, she showed signs of being something special. After a little break, she came back to me for another three months during her fourth winter.

In 2024, everything changed. The vet diagnosed Kimber with early signs of navicular in her right front foot. It was a tough blow. The year that followed was full of rest, vet visits, and even a trip to NC State‚Äôs vet school. But through corrective shoeing, injections, and time to heal, hope returned. 

At ‚ÄòShoot for Hope‚Äô in Lumberton, NC, I got in the saddle and Kimber took 4th. Most recently, she laid down another solid run at the Vernal Brothers Classic in Columbiana, OH, placing 3rd.

Her journey is one of grit, heart, and resilience. The goal now is to take her comfortably through the Derby Non-Pro this fall, with Ellie back in the saddle üêé

Kimber‚Äôs already overcome obstacles that could‚Äôve ended her career before it even began‚Äîbut she‚Äôs not done. With the right care and the same fire she‚Äôs always had, we‚Äôre hopeful for a future filled with meaningful moments‚Äîwhether that‚Äôs in the arena or out. No matter where this road leads, she has a beautiful purpose ahead of her. ü§é

{'edges': [{'node': {'text': 'I was recently asked some questions about balloons in my comments‚Ä¶ so here are a few quick tips for anyone curious about how balloons work in mounted shooting:

1.	Use regular air! No helium or gas needed‚Äîjust a hand pump, small compressor, or CO‚ÇÇ tank will do the trick.

2.	Fill to about 6‚Äì8 inches in diameter. That‚Äôs the sweet spot for easy popping without premature bursts.

3.	Keep them firm, not too tight. One that‚Äôs too tight might pop before you even get to it!

4.	Soft = a no-go. If it looks sad and saggy, add more air. Balloons need enough pressure to react to the powder blast.

Mounted shooting might look simple, but even the balloons have their own science! Got more questions? Drop them in the comments‚ÄîI love sharing the behind-the-scenes of the sport! üéàüî´üí•üêé

{'edges': [{'node': {'text': 'So you want to get into mounted shooting?
I still remember my first run‚Äînerves, excitement, and a whole lot of trial and error. If you‚Äôre thinking about jumping into this wild, addicting sport, here are a few things I wish someone had told me:

1.	Start with a horse you trust. If your horse isn‚Äôt confident, you won‚Äôt be either. Find one that‚Äôs calm, responsive, and willing to learn with you.

2.	Get help early. Whether it‚Äôs clinics, a trainer, or just someone in the sport who knows their stuff‚Äîdon‚Äôt be afraid to ask questions and soak it all in.

3.	Don‚Äôt rush it. You‚Äôll want to go fast (we all do), but control comes first. The speed will come with confidence.

4.	Gear matters. The right holsters, tack, and practice pistols make everything smoother. Invest in good stuff when you can.

5.	Enjoy the ride. The community is amazing, the adrenaline is real, and every run teaches you something new. Don‚Äôt forget to have fun.

It‚Äôs not just a sport‚Äîit‚Äôs a journey. And every shooter started somewhere. üí•üî´üí™üèº

üé•: @katebowserphotography

{'edges': [{'node': {'text': 'Making the right thing easy‚Ä¶

A trotting transition for a sticky horse needs to be asked for as gently as possible but as firmly as necessary - and then rewarded. 

This is best done with the rhythm of the Life in your body to begin with, using tools only when necessary, as this is closer to the natural ways horses communicate. 

Effectiveness is key here, both in the subtle side as well as the more firm side.
